{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cf402741-e2a0-438e-970a-fe5dc5e05d33","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`dotnet run --project`** — builds and runs your server automatically.\n- Your C# server must read JSON-RPC messages from stdin and write responses to stdout (use a library like `ModelContextProtocol` or `McpDotNet`).\n- Make sure your server does **not** write logs to stdout — use stderr instead.\n\nIf you've already published the server as a standalone executable, replace the command:\n\n```json\n\"command\": \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer\"\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"58f47e64-4dbc-4945-92ac-ce4e8393ee05","outputTokens":319,"requestId":"F042:1A905D:125E538:14B8EA3:69F940F0"},"id":"dcfea8a0-b188-4255-be55-b1e7f7b03887","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:59:37.238Z","parentId":"8401597b-568c-42cb-91c4-569819d06f37"}
